  "prompt": "Why is a crush called a crush?",
  "response": "The term \"crush\" in the context of romantic infatuation is believed to have originated in the late 19th century. While the exact etymology is not definitively known, there are a few theories:\n\n1. The word may derive from the verb \"to crush,\" suggesting the intense, almost overwhelming feeling of attraction that can metaphorically \"crush\" or overwhelm someone's emotions.\n\n2. It might relate to the idea of being \"crushed\" by one's feelings or the intensity of romantic emotion.\n\n3. Some linguists suggest it could be a shortened form of \"mash,\" which was a slang term for infatuation in the late 1800s.\n\nThe first recorded use of \"crush\" in this romantic sense dates back to around the 1880s, initially meaning an intense but usually short-lived infatuation, typically associated with young people.\n\nWhile the precise origin remains somewhat uncertain, the term effectively captures the powerful, sometimes consuming nature of romantic attraction, especially for younger individuals.",
